If $C=\frac{5}{9}(F-32)$, what is $F$ when $C=20$?
inference: Final Answer: \\boxed{68}. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth: We have $20 = \frac59(F-32)$.  Multiplying both sides by 9 to get rid of the fraction gives  \[9\cdot 20 = 9\cdot \frac59 (F-32),\] so $180 = 5(F-32)$.  We could distribute on the right-hand side, but it's a bit faster to divide both sides by 5, giving $36 = F-32$.  Adding 32 to both sides gives $F = \boxed{68}$.
